Camille Auer wanted to fix her sex, diagnosed with mental illness, and now she's doing art on the subject - "People should have a right to their own bodies"
There are dozens of patient stories hanging from the ceiling of the project room gallery of the Academy of Fine Arts.
Every one of them says Camille Auer's name.
Papers tell a multi-annual story about how outsiders have written down their interpretation of Auer and his identity.
Decided for him who he was.
"I wanted to tell you my personal treatment history to make the violence of the process visible," Auer says.
By the process, he refers to the sex correction process.
It is often a period of years of research involving meetings with psychologists, psychiatrists, nurses and doctors.
The process starts with a referral to diagnostic studies of "gender identity disorder" carried out in Tampere and Helsinki.
With Auer, the process started four years ago.
Even before this, she had used the estrogen she had ordered over the Internet and was already very advanced in her own repair process.
She felt she was a woman, but according to Finnish law a person must undergo a correction process so that the sex can also be corrected legally.
Translakis, i.e. the law establishing the sex of the transsexual (563/2002) obliges transgenders to force sterilisation in order to get the right sex into the population register centre and passport, for example.
At present, every sex repairer is required to have a psychiatric diagnosis and a certificate of reproductive disability.
A person has the right to decide his own body.
"This situation is intolerable and violates human rights," says Auer.
The reform of the law has been discussed in Finland for a long time.
The UN Human Rights Council has made eight observations on the law and the European Court of Justice has a precedent which obliges the parties to the European Convention on Human Rights to respect their right to self-determination.
The previous Finnish government prepared a change of law under the leadership of Susanne Huovinen, then Minister of Social Affairs and Health.
The elections came and the True Finns came to the government.
Now the law change is stuck again.
It is a question of domestic political disputes which do not even have anything to do with this law.
"The board does not want to put it on the table because there are disagreements within the board about changing the law," says Frank Johansson, Executive Director of Amnesty Finland's Department.
The front part of the exhibition space is dominated by two large installations.
One consists of the packaging and instructions for use of the medicines used by Auer.
In the patient history installation, any visitor can read, for example, the interpretation of the transpol psychologist at Tampere University Hospital in Auer.
The psychologist met Camille Auer twice and based on these he wrote a report that would define Auer's right to care and help.
The sense of the reality to be studied appears to be prone to wavering.
The study subject's perception of himself appears fragmentedly at the border level and the unstable personality traits are highlighted.
Auer didn't recognize himself from these descriptions.
"It was a shock to hear that I was diagnosed as mentally ill," Auer says.
An even greater shock was when Auer was not given sex correction treatment.
According to the nursing staff, his resources were not sufficient to start the process.
He was denied his own identity.
On 11 February 2015, Auer walked out of the meeting and kicked the waiting lobby of the transpol into the ground.
Later, that television produced a work of art called Monument for the Excluded, in which Auer reflected his experience of power and its use.
"It's crazy that any person who is defined as a woman at birth can enlarge their breasts, but you need a diagnosis to remove their breasts," Auer says.
Your body is not yours if you feel you are anything other than the number of genders defined at birth.
Unfortunately, Auer's experience is not unique.
For many, the sex repair process is harder for mental reasons than for purely medical operations.
Those who go through it meet dozens of people who have to justify their own existence and their right to their own sexual experience.
"It's crazy that people who are in need of support and help are denied treatment, arguing that their resources are not enough," says Auer.
Many who seek the process have psychological symptoms: depression, anxiety, possible bullying experiences.
With these in mind, medical personnel may prescribe that treatment cannot be initiated.
"To prevent treatment and help can put a person in an even worse situation than it was before the process started," says Auer.
Auer's personal exhibition also deals with anxiety and thoughts about suicide.
In the text of the exhibition publication Auer writes: "I have had suicidal thoughts throughout my adult life and that is something people usually find difficult to digest".
Depression has been treated with drugs and when Auer started using hormones, it got easier.
He had finally been able to lyric the feelings that had existed since childhood and teenagers.
Why the wide jaw didn't seem to fit into its own body and why the breast muscles had to be round instead of a flat chest.
What's important to Auer is that there are people around him who see him.
Being seen is a basic need.
"You have to justify yourself so much by talking, dressing yourself, using your voice and moving," he says.
Now Auer feels he's already been seen. He exists as a woman.
At the beginning of the process, however, the random comments of loved ones could hurt a lot.
It hurts the most when people close to you get wrong.
"They should know and they know who I am, but they will not agree or be able to internalize it," he continues.
But not all transhumans need physical changes.
They do not suffer from body dysphoria, or body conflict, where the body or parts of it can cause anxiety and even physical pain.
However, without the use of hormones and the long research process, there can be no formal confirmation of their own gender.
"There is no medical basis for these studies," says Auer.
And it's true.
In Denmark, for example, in June 2014, Parliament adopted a new procedure for the recognition of legal sex.
The new legislation is based on the right to self-determination in relation to legal sex.
An adult applicant submits a written application for a new personal identity code stating that he or she feels that he or she is of the opposite sex.
After six months of reflection, the applicant confirms his application in writing and the Ministry gives the applicant a new personal identity code.
This right of self-determination is also required in Finland and the Auer exhibition crystallizes this requirement.
It has not been a therapy experience for the artist, but an exhibition is a political and artistic collection of works.
I want to believe that art is still important and that it can bring about political change at a time when politicians have forgotten human rights.
