The Civil Rights Organisation issued a travel warning to Missouri
The National NAACP for African-American civil rights has issued a travel warning for Missouri, due to discriminatory state practices and racist attacks there.
"The travel notice for the NAACP Missouri enters into force on 28 August 2017 and calls on African-American tourists, visitors and locals to pay particular attention and to exercise extreme caution when travelling to a state where there have recently been numerous questionable racial events", states the Association's press release.
The recent law in Missouri makes it difficult for cases of discrimination to be brought to justice, and the implementation of state law is disproportionate to minorities, which, according to NACP, led to the issuing of a travel warning.
"People's civil rights are being violated.
They will be stopped by color and beaten or killed," Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP Missouri, said to Kansas City Star.
"We've never heard of so many cases in such a short time."
The Missouri travel announcement is the first warning of the United States State.
The organisation mentioned racist comments against African-American students at Missouri University and the death of 28-year-old black Tory Sanders from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year, driving through the state when his car ran out of fuel, and the Missouri police arrested him for not being charged with a crime.
The travel bulletin also referred to the Missouri Justice Minister's report that 75 percent of the black driver is more likely to be stopped by the police than by the white.
"The purpose of the travel information report is to advise people to be on guard and warn their families, friends and colleagues about what can happen in Missouri," Chapel says.
"People need to prepare themselves, for example, by including money to pay bail or by telling relatives that they are going to travel through the state."
According to the FBI, 100 hate crimes were recorded in Missouri in 2015, the sixteenth largest in the United States.
The travel warning is also a response to Missouri's new law, which makes it difficult to sue companies for discrimination in housing and employment relationships.
The ACLU organisation, which defends civil rights guaranteed by the Constitution, recently issued travel warnings to Texas and Arizona following their adoption of immigration laws which oblige the police to arrest people for illegal immigration offences.
In general, travel warnings are published by the State Department and concern other countries, but have recently been published by non-governmental organisations in response to specific laws and developments in the United States.
