Is nothing sacred anymore?
Trump's White House is now targeting the Statue of Liberty.
The most secure sign of change of power is the intervention of statues.
The Americans know this as well as anyone else: the Iraqis, together with American soldiers, took down Saddam Hussein's statue in Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the chief thinkers of Trump's regime, well knew what he was doing in a heated debate with CNN channel Jim Acosta.
Miller didn't exactly criticize the statue itself.
Had he done so, he would have been attacked by huge herds of cruise organizers and characters imitating the Statue of Liberty.
His attack was on the significance of the statue, and especially the fact that in 1903 Emma Lazarus' poem – 17 years after the statue was completed – was added to its pedestal.
Thus Miller shone at Acosta: "I don't want to go into its history now, but the Statue of Liberty... is a symbol of the American freedom that illuminates the whole world.
The poem was later added and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller was not wrong in himself, but it is not just history, as he himself said.
The most important are the touching words of Lazarus, the only ones of their kind in which the state calls not only the immigrants but the "poorest of the poor": "Your tired, your Poor, / Your huddled masses yearning to break the free, / The written relief of your theme store."
The poem is now more timely than ever.
Miller was not a literary critic, and he made it clear that the 'poorest' are not welcome in Trump's United States.
The dispute about the importance of the Statue of Liberty is part of a wider political and cultural dispute about the importance of the United States.
After Lazarus ' death, his friends campaigned for a poem to be attached to his statue's pedestal, knowing well that the act was a powerful political one.
The purpose of the statue was to express the links between French and American republicanism by the classical symbol, the feminine incarnation of freedom.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in his poem the female character is no longer abstract, but has a voice.
And it gives itself a new name: the mother of the exiles.
Linking the poem to the image was a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on the American idea of nationality.
Lazarus changed the significance of the statue, and the right has long wanted to turn it back into the original.
