Blocking Critics on Facebook: Do not run for public office if you can't stand criticism
Our country's father knew what bad publicity was.
The Americans loved George Washington, but soon the newspapers began to criticize him for all possible domestic politics, always on his political principles.
I'm sure the criticism was very annoying.
But he didn't silence his critics.
"If freedom of speech is removed, we may be led as stupid and silent as sheep for slaughter," Washington said in 1783.
Which brings us to the governor of Maryland, Larry Hogan, who should learn from Washington.
Hogan's staff has removed at least 450 comments from his official Facebook page and has blocked their performers.
The U.S. Civil Rights Federation sued Hogan earlier this week.
His staff considered the challenge to be unjustified, and the attitude was also trivial on the web.
"What difference does it make? This is just Facebook," many commentators.
But it matters.
Especially in Hogan's case.
Hogan is an amazingly popular Republican governor of a Democratic state.
He has received the second-best estimates of his operations among the 50 governors.
Hogan's not sensitive to hotheads.
He has led the state firmly and held firmly to principles.
He has also used Facebook as the main channel of communication with his voters and published a picture of a bald head in chemotherapy there.
Therefore, blocking users entering the Governor's Facebook page is unnecessary and even dangerous. The Governor's page is a public and official forum maintained by his staff with tax funds.
Hogan's publicist, Amelia Chase, defended the governor's actions in an interview with Washington Post, who said that it was only a question of moderating comments.
However, branding commentators as trolls, spammers or haters is too easy.
The Washington Post interviewed people who were blocked by Hogan on Facebook.
They turned out to be ordinary people who wanted to talk to the leaders they chose, not trolls, but teachers, entrepreneurs and pastors, for example.
They reported that their comments were respectful, considerate, and proper.
In his comment the pastor quoted the Bible; he wanted to appeal to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Maryland Bowie was not hostile but asked about hate crimes.
"I politely expressed my disappointment at Hogan's failure to comment on hate crimes and other recent news," he wrote in the comments on the Washington Post report.
Nor can I accept that when more people comment on the same issue, they are immediately regarded as an organised group and ignored as a large group of citizens concerned.
The governor's staff called the comments a "focused attack."
In the Facebook era, communication is easy to manage by blocking a critic or removing a critical comment.
In the old days, we should have sent staff to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials, or arrested and silenced protestors.
In reality, however, it is the same thing, now only digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official accused of shackling Facebook and other social media channels.
He's been sued by Twitter users blocked by President Trump.
The first important decision was taken last week in Virginia.
According to Judge James C. Cacheris of the Alexandria District Court, the Loudou County government violated the first amendment of the U.S. Constitution by blocking the voter on Facebook.
And the U.S. Civil Rights Federation went to talk to the Republican Governor of Kentucky, Matt Bevin, about the use of Twitter and Facebook.
This shouldn't be hard.
In Washington's day, cheap postage had a similar effect to that of the Internet today.
The number of newspapers quadrupled from 1776 to 1800, and anonymous writers hammered Washington.
There were trolls back then.
The titles Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius wrote letters in the newspapers in which they barked at Washington's decisions.
The President's office was flooded with petitions criticising Jay's agreement, the United States-British Cooperation, Trade and Shipping Agreement, as shown in the documents collected by the Papers of George Washington Network Project.
But he did not silence his critics.
Freedom of speech, freedom of opinion and freedom of debate are the cornerstones of our nation.
Real leadership means accepting this fact.
