Poverty and Death in Indonesia's Gold Land
Bardina Degei doesn't use a stove for cooking.
Even the boiler is rarely used.
Degei lives in a wooden building in Enarotal, the capital of the Paniai region, located in the troubled province of Papua Indonesia. When he prepares dinner, he usually puts a sweet potato – locally "not" – directly into the fireplace.
Half an hour later, the sweet potato burned to the ground will be devoured with bare, unwashed hands.
There are no furniture in Degei's home. He sits on a muddy ground floor, where he usually does his daily chores, such as washing in murky water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet is provided by a bucket in the roofless room.
Degei is the youngest of her husband's four wives and has not been assigned fields to be cared for.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous: most of the men in the village are unemployed and many drink a lot, and soldiers must be taken into account.
"No one dares walk through the village after five at night," Degei says.
This is a rare peek into everyday life in Papuan highlands, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969. The annexation was preceded by a controversial referendum in which 1,026 villages were forced to vote publicly in front of the occupying forces.
The local independence movement, which opposed the Dutch power, quickly turned its anger on the Jakarta government, which is holding the region under strict control and preventing foreign journalists and human rights observers from entering it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua. The eastern part of the island belongs to Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is remote and crass. The trip starts with an hour and a half flight from the province capital, Jayapura, to Nabire, and continues on a five-hour driving trip with a rental car.
There's no public transport here.
The town of about 19 000 inhabitants has wooden houses surrounded by bamboos, whose corrugated roofs have been dyed into yellow browns by rust.
Few Indonesians have been here, not to mention journalists and foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries came to Papua, the Mee Pago tribes worshiped the god Uga Tamee.
Other changes have taken place.
"We didn't have clothes like this," Degei says. He means a colorful, hand-woven tapering cap, dark skirt and brightly colored blouse.
"In the past, all we had were leaves covered in our bodies."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its inhabitants living below the poverty line, and child mortality and illiteracy are among the highest in Asia.
But it's also Indonesia's golden land.
Paniai is a high-rise area about the size of New Jersey, with 153 000 inhabitants, just 100 kilometres from Pania is Grasberg, the largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix, USA.
In 2015, the mine produced $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper for Freeport.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in wood reserves.
However, these riches bring misery to the Papuans, for they mean the suffocating presence of a strong Indonesian army.
In 2005, the New York Times revealed that Freeport paid almost $20 million to local military personnel and military local units between 1998 and 2004, with individual officers being paid up to $150,000.
Papua's demands for greater self-determination threaten this source of income and are silenced without mercy.
According to human rights activists, since 1969 the Indonesian army has killed more than 500 000 beanmen and raped, tortured and imprisoned thousands.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, mass killings in the highlands of the Papuan tribes in the 1970s took on the scale of genocide.
Last year the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 people in the region during peaceful demonstrations.
The report by the Brisbane Archdiocese of 2016 contains stories of the atrocities of the previous year, such as executions without trial, torture – rape and electrocution are particularly popular methods – and ruthless attacks towards peaceful demonstrations.
"It is difficult to calculate the number of victims because there are weekly cases," says Andreas Harsono, Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
Screws have been tightened when Papua's natural resources attract migrants from other parts of Indonesia.
Of the 3.5 million inhabitants of the Province, 83 percent are Christians, but the population structure is changing as Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawes move into the region in the hope of a better livelihood for Muslims.
Javawarung food stalls sell fried chicken and gado-gado vegetables in peanut sauce.
It's hard for the locals to compete.
"The movers have started selling chicken and vegetables in the market place at lower prices than the locals," says 24-year-old Abeth You, who comes from Pania and moved to the province's capital for work.
"Local women lost their clients."
In his 2014 election campaign, the Indonesian President, Joko Widodo – nicknamed Jokowi – promised to tackle the injustices and human rights violations in Papua.
Papua consists of 29 regions, and this former carpenter won the vote in 27 areas, including Paniai, on his way to the Presidential Palace of Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts were broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 and waited for him to fulfill our wishes and restore justice," You says.
The Panic experienced some kind of wavebed just two months after Jokow's inaugural ceremony in October.
Eleven children were singing carols by a fire in Enarotal on 7 December 2014, when two Indonesian soldiers appeared from the dark on motorcycles.
Scared kids told the soldiers that they should use headlights.
One of the soldiers did not like the remark, and according to the local pastor Yavedt Tebai, he returned with four soldiers.
According to the reports of the victims and witnesses, the children were captured and beaten with rifles by drunken soldiers.
That's how one of the soldiers fired at the children.
One of the children, a 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, fell into a coma as a result of assault.
A few hours later, the building of the State Election Commission near the scene was set on fire, and the next day began to happen.
About a thousand beanmen — young men and women and children — met in front of a local police station and an army command center in the football field to demand justice.
