The new results of the Swedish asylum seekers' age tests were published
The latest results of the Swedish asylum seekers' medical age tests have been published. The results of the new evaluation method reveal that over 80% of those tested were found to be over 18 years of age. However, not everyone considers the tests reliable.
The Swedish National Bureau of Legal Medicine started testing earlier this year.
A new test was introduced after the Swedish Immigration Service was criticised for failing to identify the actual age of applicants who claimed to be minors.
The Finnish Immigration Service has carried out 6 880 tests so far, and the Finnish Legal Service has now published the results of 2 481 tests. The tests were carried out between mid-March and the end of July 2017.
Eighty per cent of the tests, i.e. in 2002, the asylum seeker was determined to be over 18 years of age, and in 25 cases the National Bureau of Legal Affairs determined that the tests were "possibly 18 years of age or older".
In 432 cases, it was concluded that the asylum seeker is ‘possibly under 18'.
The tests were carried out only in cases where there was reason to suspect the age indicated by the applicant.
Johan Göransson of the Department of Legal Medicine reports that the results are consistent with the results of previous months.
"The figures are quite uniform. Big differences in the statistics of previous months are not visible," he told The Local.
Although a large number of applicants were determined to be over 18 years of age, this does not necessarily mean that they have lied about their age.
In May, the Agency published the results of the 581 tests and indicated that 442 cases had ‘references to the fact that the study is 18 years old or older'.
When Svenska Dagbladet examined the same results, it turned out that 243 cases had been openly told by the applicant that it was turning 18 this year.
The medical age assessment method used in the tests takes X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRIs of knee joints, and then dentists and radiologists analyse the images.
One of the sceptics is the Karolininen Institute's endocrinologist Claude Marcus, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans.
"I have had reason to think about it, and I believe that the method used is not the right one.
The definition of biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't determine the age for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can," he said to Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson of the Bureau of Legal Affairs defended the accuracy of the tests: "You can generally say that the risk of determining a child as an adult is small.
The risk is greatest in a situation where the test is about to turn 18 and the risk is about 10 per cent."
