The NHS prescribes to 10 000 controversial anti-HIV medicines
As of September, patients may be prescribed a ‘reversible' anti-HIV medicine. In the Supreme Court, a dispute was brought to an end regarding the funding of the medicine in the UK public health system (NHS).
The NHS reported that Pre-exposure Prophylaxis (PrEP) is prescribed to approximately 10,000 people during the first three years of the trial and that pre-coitus drug has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by approximately 86% in high-risk individuals.
The NHS agreed to finance the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld the judgment of the Supreme Court last year, according to which the NHS is able to pay for the medicine PrEP, although it claims that it should be financed by the local authorities.
Simon Stevens, director of the UK NHS, called the announced decision "a major new intervention" on Thursday, and the National AIDS Organisation described it as "a crucial moment of resolution".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to receive registrations for an experiment that will be extended to other clinics in October. The experiment will reach its full range in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an anti-HIV medicine taken prior to sexual intercourse, which reduces the risk of infection.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV infection in high-risk groups.
A medicine taken before sexual intercourse means that there are enough medicines in the body to prevent HIV infection during sexual intercourse.
You can take the medicine every day or two hours before you have sex.
The treatment target group is gay men, bisexual men and transgenders, as well as people with HIV-positive partners who are not receiving effective treatment.
The clinics will select eligible candidates for the trial from men, women and transgenders, as well as from those whose HIV-positive partner is not known to receive antiretroviral therapy for their disease.
People living in England and registered for general care can also apply for a trial at their local sexual health clinic.
The programme costs GBP 10 million and this week the UK NHS signed a contract for medicines following an international tender.
The purpose of the trial is to assess the potential of PrEP by collecting extensive clinical evidence of its targeting, taking and implementation.
"This important new intervention should complement and intensify the already existing diverse and increasingly effective means of preventing HIV," Stevens says.
"It is yet another significant achievement in the struggle of more than 30 years to solve one of mankind's greatest health challenges."
"This is a crucial moment in the fight against HIV", says Deborah Gold, Director of National AIDS.
"If PrEP is applied correctly to those in need and at risk, it can have a revolutionary effect on the HIV epidemic in England.
As of September, risk groups will receive an NHS-funded trial of medicine that they can decide independently on without the need to negotiate with a partner; it will have a empowering effect which will improve the lives of very many people.
This is welcome news."
"The most important thing now is to ensure that the experiment is launched quickly throughout the country and that no risk group is excluded," says Ian Green, Director of Terrence Higgins Foundation.
"The PrEP medicine used in the experiment has been acquired and we will soon be able to protect 10 000 people at risk from HIV infection."
"The launch of the PrEP trial is a welcome event that lasted for several months because of the government's slow-down," says Sharon Hodgson, Minister of Health of the Shadow Government.
"We have evidence that the medicine can have a revolutionary effect on our work to prevent HIV and stop the spread of this threatening disease.
The experiment will help us to better understand the real benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the experiment is launched as soon as possible throughout the country, so that we can protect those exposed to HIV and get another step closer to the situation in which the spread of HIV in society has been halted."
