That's when he noticed a message from his high school friend:
"Police just killed an 18-year-old kid, and his body is still on the street."
Confused, he noticed that no one else had posted the same information to his feed. That's why he closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
His timeline had numerous retweets from @TheePharoah.
The username belongs to a rapper in St. Louis who tweeted in real time about Michael Brown's death, and the white police had shot an unarmed 18-year-old black Brown in Ferguson, Missouri.
The user had also posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body on the street where it was left for four hours.
"This is incredible," Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to him and his community.
He put his phone away, and when he returned to Twitter later that night, people were told that people were gathering on Canfield Drive.
The users posted pictures of police tape and screaming people and the man who claimed to be Brown's father, who was wearing a sign saying, "Ferguson Police just killed my unarmed son!"
Ferrell followed a real-time video of a police officer standing in front of protestors with a barking dog.
He also says he saw a video of another cop setting up his rifle and screaming, "I'm gonna kill all of you... animals."
"This isn't normal," Ferrell remembers saying.
"It wasn't the kind of murder we're used to and could be called typical.
That's when I felt the chills.
I was angry and I cried."
He booked a return flight home for the next day.
The plane landed at 11 o'clock in the evening, and Ferrell picked up his six - year - old daughter from his father's house and decided that they would leave for Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrelli and Ferguson over the next three years has been the documentary "Whose Streets?". It was premiered in cinemas on 11 August 2017.
The film is a story of survival and demonstration, love and loss, as well as strength and perseverance from the point of view of the local people who went to the streets to demand answers.
When Ferrell drove towards Ferguson with his daughter in a flower dress and a crown matching it, they had another conversation about "what it's like to live black and under what conditions." They had talked about it countless times before that morning.
"Do you remember when I told you how black people have had to fight for the things they believe in?" Ferrell remembers saying to his daughter.
"We're going to Ferguson because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, and that's not right."
"I couldn't stop taking my daughter with me," Ferrell told me later.
"Today's events are... the culmination of events in the past.
My daughter has a right to know that and to grow into it.
He must have the ability to act and organize, but he must also know the different layers and conditions of the experience of living in black, and he must know what we must do to be freed, to free ourselves.
Although fortunately I have been able to protect him from blatant racism, he is still like all the other black girls.
I feel that I would harm him if I protected him from reality."
Their first stop in Ferguson was the South Florissant Road, located opposite the police station, which became the camp place for activists, waiting for information on the case and finally finding out that the police would not be prosecuted.
From there, Ferrell and his daughter went to help a local entrepreneur who made lunch packages.
They packed lunches in bags and distributed them to protestors.
Ferrell gradually began to view activism in a new way.
"My activity changed completely after 9 August," he says. While studying at Missouri University in St. Louis, Ferrell was the chairman of the Association of Minority Nurse Students. At that time he focused on food law and health differences in black communities.
"I had no experience of organizing.
Somehow it just happened."
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, the assistant director of the documentary.
Folayan said that he and photographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar "simply wanted to tell" what was happening.
Ferrelli's mind was squirming with suspicion, and he asked, "Do you really want to tell me what's going on, or do you want a story that you can take advantage of?"
The suspicion was based on the countless occasions when people, usually whites, had appeared in the local community to benefit only from its difficulties and persistence.
"We had heard that the people born and raised in Ferguson had no common voice," Folayan said in an interview recently. "We wanted to do things differently."
Folayan had already contacted Assistant Director Damon Davis, known for his activism among sentenced prisoners.
Davis' involvement led Ferrelli to join the project together with six other locals. The film crew followed the events during the years that followed Brown's shooting.
"This is not a document where someone speaks to us or speaks for us, but we do," Davis says.
"The most important thing for me was how local people are presented in the film because I am represented in the same way."
According to Folayan, the intention was not to focus on Ferrelli's experiences because it was intended to show that the popular movement "is not a charismatic leader but a community".
That's why the documentary shows surprisingly private aspects of Ferrelli's life, such as falling in love and getting married.
"I felt pretty naked," Ferrell laughs when he tells how it felt to see the movie for the first time.
"But I realized that this work and the human imagery of black people require a certain vulnerability."
In addition, Ferrelli's story goes back and brings back the role of black queer women in the wider Black Lives Matter movement.
The movement was born in the social media (#BlackLivesMatter) after the police had shot the black teenage boy Trayvon Martin in 2012. Two of the three founders identify with the Queer identity.
"The leadership of black queer women has kept the whole movement going," says Ferrell. "It's because we have to fight on many fronts constantly.
Black queer women have had to deal with everything."
Folayan agrees: "The movement is indeed maintained by black women, including many queer women."
However, he points out that Ferrell was not "self-sustained" because of his queer identity.
"He got the energy moving," Folayan says.
"It's no coincidence that he was on the front line. Black queer women live at the intersection of many things, and they have a lot at stake.
His energy is transmitted from the screen."
The news crews have long since left Ferguson, but the community and the police are still tense.
Ferrelli still has two and a half years of parole left, and he's been convicted of blocking the highway at a demonstration.
His description of the social political climate in his neighbourhood is brief and concise: "A mess."
Yet he still trusts the slogan he memorized on the streets of Ferguson three years ago:
"Our duty is to fight for our freedom.
It's our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
All we can lose is our chains."
