Manning sent samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where he served his 35-year sentence for leaking classified diplomatic telegrams to WikiLeaks.
Dewey-Hagborg's A Becoming Resemblance exhibition was opened on 2.8.2017.
It is based on two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg and Manning. Dewey-Hagborg combines technology, information technology and art in its work. Manning is a transnacent and pioneering dissident whose prison sentence Barack Obama relaxed on the third day of his term of office.
Dewey-Hagborg analyzed Manning's DNA algorithmically and created 30 portraits based on his genetic data. They are a sharp, albeit a little theoretical, statement on the customization of DNA data, ambiguity and the causality and identity underlying the interpretations.
Chelsea Manning, born Bradley Edward, has openly identified herself with women since puberty. In 2013, she was found guilty of 20 crimes, including violation of spy law, computer fraud and theft.
There was only one picture of Manning who was sentenced to prison: a granular, black and white selfie, where an uncomfortable manning sits in a car in the driver's seat.
Dewey-Hagborg had a highly popular Stranger Visions project in 2015, which he carried out in 2012.
In it he created portraits based on forensic data, DNA from cigarette butts and chewing gums, and created images of what the people involved might have looked like.
Then the artist got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning and needed a picture of their case," Dewey-Hagborg told us about the new exhibition at the press conference.
You couldn't get to Manning's house and you couldn't shoot him in prison, so the paper contacted Chelsea and asked him if he was interested in making a DNA portrait of Manning.
The artist and his imprisoned muse suddenly became correspondence friends, writing to each other for a couple of years.
They even wrote together a Suppressed Images comic book, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, describing the future in which the president would have eased Chelsea's sentence and would be able to see the exhibition.
In reality, Obama reduced Manning's sentence just a few days after the comic book was published, which was a fortunate coincidence after seven severe years in a military prison in Kansas.
It is also impressive that the exhibition is being opened right now when Donald Trump is waging his own war against data leaks and transgender soldiers and is finding new ways on Twitter to strengthen the strong divisions he was actually supposed to mitigate.
Dewey-Hagborg believes there's a purpose to everything.
On the wall of the gallery there is an artist's statement and underneath it is Manning's great autograph, where the last name (i) is marked by the heart. In his statement, the artist calls for an end to the "automatic breakdown on which gender, race, sexuality and culture are based".
On the opposite wall is Manning's DNA sequence: a long line of C, G and A letters written with a pencil.
With this combination of 200 letters – or nucleotide, as is the scientific definition used by the artist – Dewey-Hagborg wants to illustrate how similar we are all, at least from our biology.
"I hope that my exhibition will help people understand that we are equal in genetic heritage and that genetic data are very personal and open to interpretation," says Dewey-Hagborg. His Spurious Memories video work from 2007.
"DNA tells countless stories, and there are 30 of them on display here."
The last work of the exhibition is in its own room: page from Manning and Dewey-Hagborg comic book.
That's where Manning's character rises out of prison like King Kong, holding a megaphone.
"If they can shut you up, they've won," the picture says.
"Never shut up."
"The text is from a letter I received from Manning," says an artist from Philadelphia.
"It's so impressive, I still get to chill."
In contrast to the comic book, Manning has not yet seen the exhibition. When Manning shows up, he is greeted by a face based on his own genetic data as a group of protestors in the middle of the exhibition space.
It is intentional, like everything else in this exhibition: for example, Manning's DNA sequence is written with a pencil at a height similar to his height (157.5 cm).
"The faces were once on the wall, but I wanted to make a crowd feel like them," says Dewey-Hagborg.
"I wanted to film the mass movement that Chelsea created, which was also behind her release."
