More and more new types of HR start-ups have entered the market, helping other companies to find out how their employees are doing.
They develop and license software that can measure employee engagement. Companies can do surveys and target certain teams and population groups, provide anonymous notification services to their employees and, in some cases, direct contact with the top management.
"Your own health can be monitored with applications such as Strava and Fitbit, but where is the company's Fitbit?" asks Jim Barnett, founder and CEO of Glint-startup in Redwood City. Glint offers companies analytics software to measure employee commitment.
Errett has been using Glint's software for three years. He says that he has gained a deeper insight into the thoughts and feelings of his employees.
The programme can be used to make quick inquiries and votes for certain teams, and it can be used to draw up a map at a glance to see in which departments the workers are most disgruntled and which of the leaders have received the weakest assessments.
Companies have understood that they have to follow the culture of the workplace so that they do not become the next Uber. The transport company has been surrounded by turmoil since a former employee wrote in his blog about a culture where workers are being harassed and those who talk about problems are being punished.
For startups such as Glint, such neglect is an attractive business opportunity.
Corporate governance, regulation and compliance are a global industry whose value according to the Let's Talk Payments website can reach over $118.7 billion by 2020.
Convercent in Denver, Colorado, is a startup that helps companies to detect and prevent inappropriate behaviour. Interest in the company increased earlier this year when Uber's reputation was hit.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
It also recently concluded an agreement with Uber.
Like Glint, Converter allows companies to make tailor-made queries, collect answers confidentially in real time and map problem areas.
In addition, employees can report inappropriate behaviour anonymously via SMS.
And if there's any reason to suspect that the director is intrusive, the complaints go directly to the company's board.
"General opinion has replaced the authorities," says Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convertworld.
He points out that if a company treats its employees badly or acts unethically, the consequences may be costly even if the authorities do not intervene; consumers can start boycotting the company and it can also lose employees and be sued.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant chain has more than 25 000 employees at 500 locations. The company has been using Convertworld for over a year because it wants to ensure that the employees are aware of the operating principles and procedures and can easily contact the headquarters.
In the past, it was the practice that if an employee wanted to report a problem, he first had to find out the telephone number or email address that could make the notification to the head office. Then he had to file an official complaint and hope that it would be taken seriously.
"It was often a frightening and unpleasant experience," says James Vitrano, Chief Legal Officer of Ruby Tuesday.
In the past, problems were hidden from leaders working in another city or state; now problems such as discrimination, harassment and unfair wages can be detected and dealt with more quickly.
"I get a more comprehensive and comprehensive understanding of the worker's reality," says Vitrano, who leads Ruby Tuesday's risk management team.
"At the same time, we protect our shareholders from employment-related litigation."
According to Quinlan, companies began to take ethics, values and employee commitment more seriously after Arthur Andersen's audit firm collapsed as a result of unethical action in the Enron scandal.
Only with the help of social media did the companies realise that they could no longer prevent public settlement of their dirty laundry.
"The hope was used as a strategy before technology came under the control of ethics," Quinlan says.
Glint and Converter provide their software as a service that is regularly charged for its use.
It is a business model and an opportunity approved by venture capital investors. Both Glint and Convertworld have venture capital investors to support them.
In February, Converter raised $10 million in funding from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, which raised $47 million in capital.
Glint received €10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners and has raised a total of $60 million in funding.
Investment is not surprising given the links between companies, business culture and venture capital.
Several studies show that employees expect more from their jobs.
In a competitive market such as Silicon Valley, good wages, and interesting projects are just the beginning.
Workers want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated and that they give their time to a genuinely useful business.
"Workers are more committed to the company's success if they enjoy the company and feel that they are being listened to and that their work is rewarding," says Nina McQueen, Director of Employee Compensation and Welfare at LinkedIn.
Investors get profits when companies succeed, companies succeed when employees commit.
Third-party analytics tools promise to strengthen employee engagement, so it is no wonder that they are of interest to investors.
According to experts in the workplace culture, knowledge of employee engagement is important,
But it will be useless if no action is taken on the basis of it.
If a company requests feedback from its employees, it may be considered as a sign of change.
And if change does not come fast enough or nothing changes, disappointment can reduce the commitment of workers.
"If you ask for four thousand proposals, you have to be ready to have four thousand discussions," says Russell Raath, CEO of the management consulting company Kotter International, who has seen companies rely too much on mere data collection.
"If the company fails to take action, the employees will start to wonder if they were heard
and do their opinions matter at all.
If the company doesn't care about them, why should they care about the company?"
According to Errett, Madison Reed is currently conducting personnel surveys on a monthly basis and is able to tackle the problem on the same day as it is announced in Glint.
After collecting feedback on slow decision-making and quality of communication from frustrated workers, Errett was able to change teams and organise communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday has a better understanding of its employees and hopes that a deeper understanding will help them to improve the long-term sustainability of their employees in a sector known for their high turnover.
"If a company does not commit itself to creating a culture of transparency, it will lose its employees," says Vitrano.
"If it loses employees, it also loses customers.
And without customers, there are no companies."
