Origin of a comic book: The Story of a Castle
The small Scottish castle in Kent County is now known as Squeeze's music video and Margaret Thatcher's hideout from the 1970s and 1980s.
But it has 700 years of tumultuous history behind it. Now this charming place in the Bewli Valley is the subject of a comic book written by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-haired writer fond of old documents.
"I think it's great to be able to study the text written by someone who died over 300 years ago," Rhodes says sorely.
"I feel a personal connection as I hold the letter in my hand."
The book of Rhodes, A Castle in England, tells the stories of families living in Scotland from the Middle Ages to the Edvardian Ages. Each story is illustrated by a different artist, a promising British cartoonist: Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer or Isabel Greenberg.
This is not Rhodes' first book based on archives. In 2014, he appeared from Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories, inspired by documents from the British National Library. The project was emotional.
"I was moved to tears when I noticed a thumbprint in the letter. The letter was written by a double agent who worked for the Jacobites in the 18th century," Rhodes says.
"It was his fingerprints!
And the letters smell like smoke, because fire was then used as lighting.
Three centuries later, the smell makes the reader feel that he is on the spot.
I love archives!"
An old-fashioned writer was able to live in the castle for almost four months with the support of the National Trust Foundation and the British National Art Council, which felt too good to be true. He admits that he could not be in the castle without delay a little longer than would have been desirable.
He spent days studying Victorian "new" castles, archives, treasures and raritys, such as hyena heads hanging on walls and bottles in moats for centuries.
He traveled around the ruins and estates of the old castle and talked with the rangers, gardeners, and sometimes also the illustrious artists of the book.
In the evenings, he "took whiskey and started writing."
Scotland's closer history is quite unknown, since the castle was completely transferred to the National Trust only after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived about ten years later, the Foundation's staff were just about to start going through the archive. Rhodes describes that the archives had been kept for hundreds of years using the same method: taking all the extras to the attic.
The archives contained journals, letters from the times of the British Empire and maps of who owned what. "You could imagine that land disputes are boring," Rhodes says. "However, here families fought for even one birch.
It occurred to me that I think we should let it go."
Some of the stories in the book go from the castle to the history of England, such as The Labourer, about a man who, shortly after the castle was completed, joined the English peasant monkey in 1381.
"Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex states that there was a riot in the castle in 1380," Rhodes says.
"The English peasant monkey started in the same area, and it occurred to me that the rebellion could start in a riot.
Maybe these events are connected?"
The other stories in the book are closely related to the history of the castle – such as The Priest, the story of the priest that Darrell's family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
The Smuggler tells the story of smuggler Arthur Darrell from the 18th century. He is said to have staged his own funeral by filling the coffin with stones (it was discovered years later when his grave was opened).
The Darrells are Rhodes' favorite family in Scotland. "The family's men seem to be quite a rascal. They were constantly in debt and bought things they couldn't afford.
The men of the Darrell family solved their debt problems by marrying wealthy old women. I see them as handsome guys who could court the heiress."
Now Rhodes is looking for new writing experiences.
He spent two weeks in Finland writing a comic book about Elämänmäki, a sanatorium in the beginning of the 20th century, where only a eutrophic plot remains.
There's a special place in Scotland Castle in his heart.
"It was sad to leave," he says.
"I didn't want to go back to this damn day."
