Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may relieve irritable bowel syndrome
Red meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare in the digestive system.
However, a recent study claims the opposite: A diet rich in meat protein and milk products may help to relieve irritable bowel syndrome.
Irritated bowel syndrome is an incurable disease that affects about 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causing abdominal cramps, swelling, recurrent or bloody diarrhoea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
People with IRR are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products. However, Washington University researchers found that essential amino acid tryptophan in protein helps the body to develop immune cells that strengthen intestinal tolerance.
According to Marco Colonna, the research director, immune cells guard the swamp and ensure that harmful microbes hiding in food do not enter the body.
Inflammatory cells are balanced by cells that strengthen tolerance, protecting the body without damaging the sensitive tissues.
If the balance falls too close to inflammation, the result may be irritable bowel syndrome.
The tests found that the immune cells that strengthen tolerance are found in mice with a specific bacterium in their intestines.
The bacteria in question need tryptophan to cause immune cells to appear. Tryptophan is one of the building blocks of proteins.
"We found a connection between the development of the bacterium Lactobacillus reuteri and the development of cells that promote tolerance.
"The more tryptophan in mice' diets, the more such immune cells they had."
If the same works in humans, a combination of the bacteria Lactobacillus reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan may enhance intestinal tolerance and reduce susceptibility to inflammation.
When studying immune cells that enhance tolerance, researcher Luisa Cervantes-Barragan found that although one group of mice had such cells, they did not exist in mice of the same mouse species that were kept separate from the other group.
He suspected that the difference was related to the microbials in the intestines of mice, the normal gastrointestinal community of bacteria, fungi and viruses.
When DNA from the intestines of mice was examined, six species of bacteria were found in mice with immune cells but not in other mice.
When Lactobacillus reuteri was administered to mice in a sterile environment that had no microbial bowels and did not develop immune cells, immune cells began to appear.
Researchers wanted to find out how bacteria affect the immune system, which raised the bacteria called Lactobacillus reuteri in fluid and transferred small amounts of fluid — without bacteria — to immature immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells developed into resistant cells.
When purified from the liquid, the active ingredient proved to be a by-product of the metabolism of tryptophan known as indol-3 lactic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the number of cells that strengthen tolerance increased by about 50 percent. When tryptophan was halved, the number of cells dropped to half the previous one.
According to Cervantes-Barragan, a person has the same cells that strengthen tolerance as a mouse, and most of us have the Lactobacillus reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not yet known whether the by-products of tryptophan from the bacteria Lactobacillus reuterus cause cells to develop in humans in the same way as in mice. However, genetic defects associated with tryptophan have been observed in patients with IG.
"We probably want to promote the development of such cells because they regulate inflammation inside the intestines," Cervantes-Barragan says.
"A high level of tryptophan combined with Lactobacillus reuter may contribute to their generalisation."
